“ You were very wicked, Mr. Heathcliff 1”
I exclaimed; “ were you not ashamed to dis-
turb the dead?”

“ I disturbed nobody, Nelly,” he replied;
“ and I gave some ease to myself. I shall be
a great deal more comfortable now; and you’ll
have a better chance of keeping me tin»
derground, when I get there. Disturbed her?
No! she has disturbed me, night and day,
through eighteen years—incessantly—remorse-
lessly—till yesternight—and yesternight, I was
tranquil. I dreamt I was sleeping the last

sleep, by that sleeper, with my heart stopped,
and my cheek frozen against hers.”

“ And if she had been dissolved into earth,
or worse, what would you have dreamt of

then?” I said.

